1. Diagram: A diagram showing a block on an inclined plane with arrows representing the gravitational force, normal force, and frictional force.

2. Description: 
The diagram depicts a block resting on an inclined plane. Three primary forces act on the block:

- Gravitational Force (Fg): This force acts vertically downward, represented by an arrow pointing from the center of the block straight down toward the ground. The gravitational force can be decomposed into two components: one parallel to the inclined plane (Fg_parallel) and one perpendicular to the inclined plane (Fg_perpendicular).

- Normal Force (Fn): This force acts perpendicular to the surface of the inclined plane, represented by an arrow pointing from the center of the block perpendicular to the surface of the inclined plane. The normal force is the reaction force provided by the plane and is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the perpendicular component of the gravitational force (Fg_perpendicular).

- Frictional Force (Ff): This force acts parallel to the surface of the inclined plane, opposing any potential motion of the block. It is represented by an arrow pointing from the center of the block up the plane. The frictional force adjusts to match the parallel component of the gravitational force (Fg_parallel) to keep the block static.

The inclined plane makes an angle θ with the horizontal. The gravitational force components are calculated as:
- Fg_parallel = Fg * sin(θ)
- Fg_perpendicular = Fg * cos(θ)

The balance of forces ensures the block remains stationary. The normal force (Fn) balances Fg_perpendicular, and the frictional force (Ff) balances Fg_parallel.
